src_text: Teknolohikal nga determinismo an termino nga nagdadara han haluag nga sakop han mga ideya han buruhaton, tikang ha duso-teknolohiya o an kinahanglan nga teknolohiya ngadto han istrikto nga kahulugan nga an kapalaran han tawo iginduduso ha ilarom han lohika nga maylabot an balaud han sensya ngan an ira pagpapakita ha teknolohiya.
ref_text: Technological determinism is a term that encompasses a wide range of ideas in practice, from technology-push or the technological imperative to a strict sense that human destiny is driven by an underlying logic associated with scientific laws and their manifestation in technology.
hyp_text: Technological determinism is a term that describes an array of theoretical perspectives which ascribe social and cultural change to technology. In this view, changes in technology—not changes in human culture—act as the engine of change in society. Technological determinism can be divided into two overarching forms: hard and soft determinism. Hard determinism is the view that technology develops independent of social concerns. This theory can be traced back to the ideas of the US philosopher Thorstein Veblen, and was popularized by the historian Lynn White. In this view, technology is a self-determining system which develops autonomously. It can only be influenced by other technology, and not by social customs or ethics. Soft determinism is a slightly more nuanced view, which says that technology is influenced by society but culture still has a chance to change it. This is the view of William Ogburn, who believed that technology may change, but only as a result of a large number of other factors. This is also the view of the social critic Neil Postman, who believed that while technology does control society, we aren’t slaves to it. In his book, Technopoly: The Surrender of Culture to Technology, Postman defines technology as “the surrender of culture to technology.” He proposes that technology changes our own norms, expectations, and social roles, in particular when he says we have become a Technopoly, where “the most important criteria for social life are economic and technical rather than political and philosophical”. In other words, technology is controlling our society and lives. However, he believes that we still have the power to control technology. He proposes that we become more critical of technological development. He states that we need to ask of every new technology that we acquire, “What will we use it for and what will it use us for?” In other words, we must become more critical of the technology we acquire and how we effect technology. Postman believes that we must control technology before it controls us.
